[normal]Executive Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]This memorandum contains written evidence submitted by PHS Space Ltd to the Science and Technology
[normal] Committee
[normal] inquiry into the European and UK Space Agencies.
[normal] R
[normal]esponses are provided to five of the six categories of information requested by the c
[normal]ommittee. However,
[normal] th
[normal]e focus of the
[normal] 
[normal]evidence relate
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]to
[normal] the space debris problem.
[normal] Some concerns
[normal] about the level of funding 
[normal]available 
[normal]in the UK 
[normal]are ide
[normal]ntified, particularly with regard to the development of 
[normal]innovative 
[normal]debris mitiga
[normal]tion / remediation technologies
[normal]. 
[normal]B
[normal]udgetary
[normal] pressures are also observed 
[normal]to 
[normal]be jeopardizing
[normal] the UK’s long-standing 
[normal]participation at important international 
[normal]debris mitigation 
[normal]committees.
[normal] 
[normal]It is noted that the UK cannot afford to ignore the debris problem if it is serious about growing the space sector to achieve a £40 billion turnover by 2030
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Indeed, part of this turnover c
[normal]ould come from th
[normal]e development 
[normal]and use 
[normal]of 
[normal]technologies
[normal] that address the debris problem
[normal].
